Here's the recommended approach using `Window` lifecycle events and `Preferences`:

**1. Create a custom `Window` subclass in `App.xaml.cs`:**

```csharp
public partial class App : Application
{
    protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    {
        var window = base.CreateWindow(activationState);

        window.Stopped += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Save draft when app goes to background
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
        };

        window.Resumed += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Restore draft when app comes back
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                page.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
        };

        window.Destroying += (s, e) =>
        {
            // Android back-button can skip Stopped entirely
            if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
                Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
        };

        return window;
    }
}
```

**2. Or, for a cleaner approach — use a `Window` subclass:**

```csharp
public class AppWindow : Window
{
    public AppWindow(Page page) : base(page) { }

    protected override void OnStopped()
    {
        base.OnStopped();
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            Preferences.Set("draft_text", page.ViewModel.DraftText);
    }

    protected override void OnResumed()
    {
        base.OnResumed();
        if (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage is NotePage page)
            page.ViewModel.DraftText = Preferences.Get("draft_text", string.Empty);
    }

    protected override void OnDestroying()
    {
        base.OnDestroying();
        Preferences.Set("draft_text",
            (Shell.Current?.CurrentPage as NotePage)?.ViewModel.DraftText ?? string.Empty);
    }
}

// In App.xaml.cs:
protected override Window CreateWindow(IActivationState? activationState)
    => new AppWindow(new AppShell());
```

**Key things to know:**

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| `Resumed` doesn't fire on first launch | Initial sequence is `Created` → `Activated`. Load saved draft in your page's `OnAppearing` too. |
| Android back button skips `Stopped` | Always save in **both** `OnStopped` and `OnDestroying`. |
| Keep handlers fast | Stay under ~2 seconds. `Preferences` is fine; avoid DB writes here. |
| `Deactivated` ≠ `Stopped` | A notification shade triggers `Deactivated` — don't save there, wait for `Stopped`. |
